    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "In terms of ease of use, it *is* ideal. The cost is about 100MB of memory (size of the DLL) iff qt5 integration is requested. QWebEngine is the qt5 replacement of QtWebkit, the \"Qt web view\" widget. I expect it's fairly common in modern Qt Applications.\r\n\r\nThere are two alternatives:\r\n1. Change the `%gui` magic to take arguments. This would also require changes to to config file, so the change can be made permanent.\r\n2. Use a hack like:\r\n```python\r\nIPYTHON=1\r\n\r\ndef ensure_QApp(*args,**kwargs):\r\n    app=None\r\n    app = QApplication.instance() or QApplication([''])\r\n\r\n    if IPYTHON:\r\n        try:\r\n            import IPython.terminal.pt_inputhooks.qt as ipqt\r\n            ipqt._appref = app\r\n        except:\r\n            pass\r\n    return app\r\n\r\napp = ensure_QApp([''])\r\nwindow = None\r\n\r\ndef main():\r\n    global app, window\r\n    window = MyMainWindow() \r\n    window.show() \r\n\r\nif __name__ == '__main__':  \r\n    main()  \r\n    app.exec_()  \r\n```\r\n\r\nThen, in IPython:\r\n```\r\n>>> import myapp # create the QApplication and shove it into IPython internals\r\n>>> %gui qt5 # activate integration, will use the event loop of OUR QApplication\r\n>>> foo.main() # show the main window, doesn't block now\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis is cumbersome, touches IP internals, requires IP-specific changes to the application and the little dance has to be redone on every kernel restart. It doesn't require changes to IP though.\r\n "
  },
